            <fr:title text="Operator fusion is like ASIC caching">Operator fusion is like ASIC caching</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>On a traditional CPU, the hardware manages <fr:link href="/M91V/" title="Caches" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/M91V/" display-uri="M91V" type="local">caching</fr:link> to ensure that data that is reused does not roundtrip through <fr:link href="/GWD5/" title="DRAM" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/GWD5/" display-uri="GWD5" type="local">DRAM</fr:link>. On an <fr:link href="/OGCRS/" title="ASIC accelerators" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/OGCRS/" display-uri="OGCRS" type="local">ASIC accelerators</fr:link>, we forego the complexity of caching to allow for more execution units. However, now if we have two operations i.e. elementwise add <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\to ]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/C00V/" title="Softmax" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/C00V/" display-uri="C00V" type="local">softmax</fr:link> this would</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li>Load the input tensors from memory (HBM on <fr:link href="/NZZ7/" title="TPU Architecture" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/NZZ7/" display-uri="NZZ7" type="local">TPU</fr:link>).</html:li>
  <html:li>Perform the elementwise add.</html:li>
  <html:li>Store the output tensor to memory.</html:li>
  <html:li>Load the input tensors from memory.</html:li>
  <html:li>Perform the softmax.</html:li>
  <html:li>Store the output tensor to memory.</html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>On a CPU, the input tensors would remain in the cache. However, this must be done explicitly on ASIC (or by the compiler in the case of Google / <fr:link href="https://kellenkanarios.com/M74N/" type="external">XLA</fr:link>).</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
